<div class="wrapper">
  <div class="page-header">
    <div>
      <div class="breadcrumb">Operating Systems / <span>Core Concepts</span></div>
      <div class="page-title">OS Core Concepts</div>
      <div class="page-meta">Kernel, memory, filesystems, drivers, and boot security</div>
    </div>
    <div class="header-pill">5 CONCEPTS</div>
  </div>
  <div class="ring-split">
    <div class="ring-pane kernel">
      <div class="pane-header"><span class="pane-icon">‚öôÔ∏è</span><span class="pane-title">Kernel Space</span><span class="ring-badge kernel-badge">RING 0 ¬∑ PRIVILEGED</span></div>
      <div class="pane-desc">The core of the OS. Has <strong class="k">full access to hardware</strong>. Manages system calls ‚Äî requests from software to the OS. Operates in privileged mode. A single bug here can compromise the entire system.</div>
      <div class="tags"><span class="tag">full hardware access</span><span class="tag">syscall handler</span><span class="tag">trusted</span></div>
      <div class="security-note">üõ° Minimising kernel attack surface is critical</div>
    </div>
    <div class="ring-pane user">
      <div class="pane-header"><span class="pane-icon">üë§</span><span class="pane-title">User Space</span><span class="ring-badge user-badge">RING 3 ¬∑ RESTRICTED</span></div>
      <div class="pane-desc">Where applications run in a <strong class="u">restricted environment</strong>. Processes are isolated from each other ‚Äî one app cannot read another's memory. Must request hardware access via syscalls to the kernel.</div>
      <div class="tags"><span class="tag">isolated processes</span><span class="tag">restricted access</span><span class="tag">syscall requests</span></div>
      <div class="security-note">üõ° Process isolation prevents lateral movement</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="syscall-bar">‚Üë syscall boundary ‚Äî user space cannot cross without kernel permission ‚Üë</div>
  <div class="concepts">
    <div class="card" style="--c:#8b5cf6">
      <div class="card-header"><div class="dot" style="--c:#8b5cf6"></div><div class="card-title">Process & Memory Management</div></div>
      <div class="card-desc">The OS schedules CPU time slices across processes and manages virtual memory through paging and segmentation ‚Äî each process gets its own isolated address space mapped to physical RAM.</div>
      <div class="card-tags"><span class="tag">paging</span><span class="tag">segmentation</span><span class="tag">virtual memory</span><span class="tag">CPU scheduling</span></div>
      <div class="card-note">üõ° ASLR ¬∑ NX Bit ¬∑ Stack Canaries protect this layer</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card" style="--c:#10b981">
      <div class="card-header"><div class="dot" style="--c:#10b981"></div><div class="card-title">Filesystems & I/O</div></div>
      <div class="card-desc">Filesystems abstract physical storage into files and directories. The OS enforces permissions (rwx), Access Control Lists (ACLs), and Mandatory Access Controls via SELinux or AppArmor. Encrypted filesystems add confidentiality.</div>
      <div class="card-tags"><span class="tag">ACLs</span><span class="tag">SELinux</span><span class="tag">AppArmor</span><span class="tag">encryption</span></div>
      <div class="card-note">üõ° DAC + MAC = layered access control</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card" style="--c:#f59e0b">
      <div class="card-header"><div class="dot" style="--c:#f59e0b"></div><div class="card-title">Device Drivers & Modules</div></div>
      <div class="card-desc">Drivers run with kernel-level privileges, making them high-value attack targets. Modern OSes mitigate this through driver signing, sandboxing, and loading modules only when needed.</div>
      <div class="card-tags"><span class="tag">kernel privileges</span><span class="tag">driver signing</span><span class="tag">sandboxing</span><span class="tag">modular loading</span></div>
      <div class="card-note">üõ° Unsigned drivers = untrusted code in Ring 0</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card" style="--c:#f97316">
      <div class="card-header"><div class="dot" style="--c:#f97316"></div><div class="card-title">Boot & Firmware</div></div>
      <div class="card-desc">The boot process initialises hardware then loads the OS kernel. UEFI Secure Boot cryptographically verifies each step ‚Äî firmware ‚Üí bootloader ‚Üí kernel ‚Äî ensuring only signed, trusted binaries execute.</div>
      <div class="card-tags"><span class="tag">UEFI</span><span class="tag">Secure Boot</span><span class="tag">chain of trust</span><span class="tag">TPM</span></div>
      <div class="card-note">üõ° Prevents bootkits and firmware-level rootkits</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
